  "articleSummary": "The article argues that embedding raw prompt strings in application code creates fragile, unversioned, and insecure systems, advocating instead for treating prompts as structured, load-bearing configuration. It highlights how string interpolation enables prompt injection—analogous to SQL injection—and introduces three TypeScript-based engineering patterns to mitigate these risks: schema-validated templates using Zod, composable prompt builders for modular assembly, and strict instruction-data separation via OpenAI/Anthropic API message formats. Targeted at software engineers and AI application developers, the piece maintains a pragmatic, tutorial-style tone while framing prompts as critical infrastructure that demands the same version control, testing, and architectural rigor as traditional code.",
